        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>A large bandwidth is needed to recover the entire width of the broad [CI] wings (FWZI = 1400 km/s) and to accurately estimate the adjacent continuum in order to subtract it from the line. For this reason we designed the spectral setup as follows: we created two spectral windows in one of the sidebands, overlapping at the centre of the [CI] line. Since only the central 1875 MHz of each spectral window have full sensitivity, we placed the centers of the two spectral windows at a distance of 1.8 GHz, in order to have a "safe" overlap of 37.5 MHz of the central "full sensitivity" part. We note that some overlap between the spw is essential, because it is possible that the spectral windows will move apart slightly during the observations (because of the Doppler correction required to remove the effects of the Earth rotation). The total exploitable bandwidth is therefore 3.675 GHz, corresponding to ~2293 km/s, which is a good compromise between "safety" and bandwidth maximisation. We note that the remaining two basebands (in the other sideband) are used to detect and map the continuum. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Based on the IRAM PdBI map of the blueshifted CO(1-0) wing (Figure 1e), the [CI](1-0) outflow is expected to extend over scales as large as ~20'' (LAS). For this reason, since our goal is to recover the most extended and diffuse [CI] emission, we request the most compact ALMA 12m array configuration, which, at these frequencies, provides an angular resolution of 0.75''. In addition, ACA is needed (and has been selected) to recover structures on scales larger than ~6''.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Since one of our goals is to detect at high significance and image the molecular outflow, our sensitivity estimates are based on the flux density expected in the faint blue-shifted wing. Our sensitivity is estimated as follows:
(i) From the CO(1-0) spectrum in Fig.1c, obtained with an angular resolution of ~1 arcsec (A-conf of the IRAM PdBI, Feruglio et al. 2013a,b), we infer a CO(1-0) peak flux density of 450 mJy and a``core-to-blue wing" flux density ratio of 7.5 (i.e. the ratio between the flux density at v=0 km/s and the one at v=-400 km/s).
(ii) We then use the total (velocity-integrated) intensity ratio of I_[CI](1-0)/I_CO(1-0) = 5.4 measured by Papadopoulos et al. (2013, 2014) by using Herschel-SPIRE data (Fig.1a) to scale the CO(1-0) flux density to the expected [CI](1-0) flux density, by taking into account their different frequencies. We obtain an expected [CI](1-0) flux density of 600 mJy at v=0 km/s and of 80 mJy at v=-400 km/s. However, since we request our Band 8 observations to be carried out with the most compact ALMA 12m array configuration, which provides an angular resolution of 0.75'', we conservatively divide these values by a factor of 2 (corresponding to (1''/0.75'')^2), to take into account the small difference in synthesised beam size between the IRAM CO(1-0) observations and the requested ALMA [CI] observations. The resulting expected [CI] flux density per synthesised beam at v=-400 km/s is thus 40 mJy/beam.
(iii) To detect the [CI] wings at a sufficient S/N across their entire width, we aim to achieve a sensitivity per synthesised beam of 4 mJy/beam in 50 km/s channels, which corresponds to a S/N=10 in the [CI] blue-shifted component at -400 km/s. Requiring a S/N of 5 would not lower the total ALMA+ACA Band 8 observing time.
We note that, although our sensitivity estimates are conservatively based on the IRAM PdBI A-conf data, which resolve out almost 50% of the total CO(1-0) emission, in this requested ALMA+ACA configuration we expect to recover most of the extended flux, and therefore we expect to achieve an even higher SNR in the [CI](1-0) wings.
The expected continuum flux density at these frequencies is of 258 mJy, as inferred from a SED fitting. The requested sensitivity will allow us to detect the continuum at high significance. Based on previous observations of the same source (Scoville et al. 2015, Feruglio et al. 2013a,b) we do not expect to spatially resolve the continuum emission.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
