        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We expect the two lines to be very broad (FWZI of 1400 km/s, Fig. 1c). In order to accurately estimate the adjacent continuum and subtract it from the lines, we request the maximum bandwidth available of 1.875 GHz (corresponding to more than 5000 km/s at these frequencies) and a spectral resolution of 3 km/s.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The 13CO(1-0) outflow is expected to extend over scales as large as 20 arcsec (LAS, Fig. 1e). For this reason we request the most compact ALMA 12m array configuration which, at these frequencies, provides an angular resolution of 3.5'' and would allow us to detect structures on scales of up to ~25'', hence ACA observations are not needed.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Since one of our goals is to detect at high significance and image the molecular outflow, our sensitivity estimates are based on the flux density expected in the faint blue-shifted wing of the 13CO(1-0) transition (i.e. the fainter of the two lines we target in the Band 3 experiment). The sensitivity is estimated as follows:
(i) Since in Band 3 the angular resolution is 3.5", we base our sensitivity estimate on the CO(1-0) spectrum obtained by Feruglio et al. (2013a) with an angular resolution of ~5" (rather than on the CO(1-0) spectrum shown in Fig.1c, which was obtained with higher angular resolution). The CO(1-0) peak flux density (at v=0 km/s) is 930 mJy.
(ii) We adopt the total (velocity-integrated) intensity ratios of I_13CO(1-0)/I_CO(1-0) = 1/50 and of I_CS(2-1)/I_13CO(1-0)=1.15 measured by Papadopoulos et al. (2013, 2014) using Herschel-SPIRE data (Fig.1a) to scale the CO(1-0) flux density to the expected 13CO(1-0) and CS(2-1) flux densities, by correcting for the frequency ratios. 
(iii) We divide these values by a factor of 2 (corresponding to (5"/3.5")^2) to take into account the difference in synthesised beam size between the IRAM CO(1-0) observations and the requested ALMA 13CO(1-0) and CS(2-1) observations. Therefore, for the peak of the line (i.e. v=0 km/s), we obtain an expected flux density per synthesised beam of 9.8 mJy/beam and 12.6 mJy/beam, respectively for the 13CO(1-0) and CS(2-1) transitions (Table 1).
(iv) To infer the expected flux density at v=-400 km/s (i.e. in the blue wing), we divide these values by 7.5 (i.e. the line core-to-blue wing ratio estimated from CO(1-0)) resulting in 1.3 mJy/beam and 1.7 mJy/beam, respectively for the 13CO(1-0) and CS(2-1) lines. To detect the broad wings of these lines at a sufficient S/N across their entire width we aim to achieve a S/N=5 in the blueshifted 13CO(1-0) component, which corresponds to a sensitivity of 0.26 mJy/beam in 50 km/s channels.
The expected continuum flux density at these frequencies is 12.7 mJy (Feruglio et al. 2013a,b). The requested sensitivity will allow us to detect the continuum at high significance. Based on previous observations of the same source (Feruglio et al. 2013a,b) we do not expect to spatially resolve the continuum emission.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
